ants-terminal (0.7.13-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Scope-tightening pass on the audit rule-pack trust boundary shipped
    in 0.7.12. The global audit_trust_command_rules bool over-granted
    after one opt-in — trusting Ants's own repo implicitly trusted every
    cloned repo the user later opened. 0.7.13 replaces the global flag
    with a per-project hash-bound trust store so trust is both narrow
    and self-invalidating.
  * Security: per-project audit rule-pack trust store. Global
    audit_trust_command_rules bool retired. Trust is keyed on
    (canonical projectPath, sha256(audit_rules.json bytes)) via three
    new Config methods: isAuditRulePackTrusted, trustAuditRulePack,
    untrustAuditRulePack. Trusting one project no longer extends to
    siblings; any edit to the rule pack invalidates trust (re-prompt
    on next open); projectPath is canonicalized via
    QFileInfo::canonicalFilePath so symlinks / trailing slashes
    resolve to a single record; ANTS_AUDIT_TRUST_UNSAFE=1 remains an
    escape hatch for CI. Legacy-bool users are re-prompted per
    project on upgrade.
  * Changed: audit dialog gains an "Untrusted rules: N" badge on the
    Detected-types row with a tooltip explaining the trust boundary
    and opt-in path; stderr qWarning copy retained for headless / CI.
  * Changed: CLAUDE.md streamlined from 325 to 147 lines (~67%
    reduction) by dropping the full project-structure tree,
    collapsing verbose audit pipeline prose, retiring the per-dep
    install-command list, and dropping the Config-keys table.
    Retained: non-obvious gotchas, design rationale, release-file
    triad rule.
  * Tests: new tests/features/audit_command_rule_trust/ lane —
    seven-invariant regression test against the new trust API
    (default-untrusted, round-trip, hash-bound invalidation,
    cross-project isolation with byte-identical packs, path
    canonicalization through symlinks + trailing slashes, idempotent
    untrust, cross-Config-instance persistence through config.json).
    Spec-first: contract written before the code.

